R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. The R Markdown format is useful because it allows us to combine text and code in a way that allows it to run and be easily read.

The RStudio IDE

An IDE, or Integrated Development Environment is a specialized text editor used to write code. There are different IDEs for different languages, and often multiple IDE options for a given language. Some IDEs, like RStudio, can even be used for multiple programming languages! Often, IDEs come with a variety of features to make programming easier.
Some examples are:

  • Auto completion prompts
  • Color coding functions or other groups of text
  • Debugging tools
  • Help options for various aspects of the IDE or code

Password Changing

Right now, your IDE likely has 4 panels, with panes for:

  • Source
  • Console
  • Environment / History / Connections / Tutorial
  • Files / Plots / Packages / Help / Viewer

For now, lets navigate to Tools > Shell where well run the following command to change our passwords to sign in to the miniDREAM environment.

passwd

You should receive prompts to enter your current password, a new password, and then to confirm the new password.
As you enter your various passwords no text will appear, but this is normal and is similar to how passwords on websites are protected with black dots during entry.

The Panes of the IDE

Console

In the console, you can execute commands one line at a time. This is really useful for trying out new things or different approaches while taking your time.
Try running the following lines of code in the console!

month <- 'June'
temperature <- 105

We just assigned values to the variables month and temperature. Variables can hold data of different types; in this case month holds a string or a type useful for storing characters and text, and temperature holds a numerical integer value. There are other data types as well.

Environment / History / Connections / Tutorial

After running the last two commands successfully, you should now see the two variables and their values displayed in the Environment pane. This pane shows all of the variables that exist currently, and their values.
Within the same pane, you can click to the History pane to see the history of the commands you have already run. Theres also the Connections pane, that shows connections youve made to supported external data sources, and the Tutorial pane that gives short lessons on things you can do in R.

Source

Running commands one at a time in the console is useful in certain situations, but with only using the console it can be hard to rerun larger sections of code, hard to remember the steps you took when looking back to the past, and hard to share your code with others. That is where the Source pane comes in!
We can open a new file by navigating to File > New File and then picking a file type. For now, lets pick R Script. In the script, you can write all of your code and save it so that it can be stored for later reference and use, or shared with colleagues to rerun.

Files / Plots / Packages / Help / Viewer

The last pane has multiple tabs: Files lists the files and folders in your current directory, or the folder that youve navigated to. Any graphs or figures that you generate with code in RStudio are displayed in the Plots pane. Packages Lists all of the packages that you have installed and their version numbers. The Help pane will display more detailed information about R functions and datasets to assist you as you write. The Viewer pane is useful for visualizing documents like this R Markdown file!

Customization

There are many settings for RStudio that you can configure to your preference!
Lets navigate to Tools > Global Options. Here we can change everything from font size to theme, and how RStudio behaves.

Programming in R with RStudio

Lets start working with data and data visualization!
The first dataset well work with is the cars dataset. We get background information about this dataset, and look at the first few entries by running:

?cars
head(cars)
##   speed dist
## 1     4    2
## 2     4   10
## 3     7    4
## 4     7   22
## 5     8   16
## 6     9   10

From the help description and the first few entries of the dataset, we can see that this dataset contains data on the distance cars take to stop given the speed that they were going, and that the data were collected in the 1920s.
We can use functions built into R, like plot(), to quickly visualize the data.

plot(cars)
title('Car Stopping Distance vs. Speed')

Aside from the built in functions, there are other packages that the R community has created that expand the functionality of R. Lets use one of those packages, ggplot2, to visualize another dataset. Well also assign the ChickWeight dataset to the variable chk so we dont have to type as much.

?ChickWeight
chk <- ChickWeight
head(chk)
##   weight Time Chick Diet
## 1     42    0     1    1
## 2     51    2     1    1
## 3     59    4     1    1
## 4     64    6     1    1
## 5     76    8     1    1
## 6     93   10     1    1

ChickWeight is a dataset that contains the weight of chicks on different diets over the first 21 days of their lives. Lets import ggplot2 so we can use it to visualize our dataset.

library('ggplot2')

We know that we want to look at the weight of each chick over time, so lets start with a plot of the dataset, and specify that we want the x axis to be time, and the y axis to be weight. After creating the base plot layer, we can add more layers to it to change the appearance of the plot. Below, well use geom_point to generate a scatter plot.

plt <- ggplot(data = chk, aes(x = Time, y = weight)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    x = 'Day of Life',
    y = 'Weight (grams)',
    title = ('Weight of Chicks at the Beginning of Life')
  )
show(plt)

This graph displays the information we gave it, but if you remember, there was data for each individual chick, and there were four diets being studied. We can use the aes mapping to further specify how data is displayed. In this case, we can color code the data for each diet.

plt <- ggplot(data = chk, aes(x = Time, y = weight)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Diet))  +
  labs(
    x = 'Day of Life',
    y = 'Weight (grams)',
    title = ('Weight of Chicks at the Beginning of Life')
  )

show(plt)

To get more detailed and look at the trends of each individual chick, and how the whole diet group performed, we can add another layer with geom_line, group the lines by chick, and color code according to diet

plt <- ggplot(data = chk, aes(x = Time, y = weight)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Diet)) + 
  geom_line(aes(group = Chick, color = Diet))  +
  labs(
    x = 'Day of Life',
    y = 'Weight (grams)',
    title = ('Weight of Chicks at the Beginning of Life')
  )

show(plt)

If we dont want a scatter or line plot, and we just want to look at the trends of the diet groups as a whole, then its as easy as switching out the layers we add to our base layer!

plt <- ggplot(data = chk, aes(x = Time, y = weight)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = Diet, color = Diet, fill = Diet), method = 'loess', formula =  'y ~ x')  +
  labs(
    x = 'Day of Life',
    y = 'Weight (grams)',
    title = ('Average Weight of Diet Groups at the Beginning of Life')
  )

show(plt)

Submitting the prediction

Youre now ready to submit! Before you can do so, you must first log in with your Synapse credentials. For security purposes, we recommend using a Synapse Personal Access Token (PAT) rather than your username and password. This token can be generated on the Synapse platform here.

Click on the blue Create New Token button. You will be asked to provide a token name - we recommend using something descriptive such as minidream. Under Token Permissions, give the token View and Modify permissions. Upon generating, you will be given a token that is ONLY AVAILABLE FOR VIEWING ONCE. Copy the token, then paste it into authToken in the code chunk below.

Note: By using rememberMe = TRUE in the login below, you will not need to provide your credentials from this point forward.

Once you copy over your PAT, go ahead and run the code chunk below.

library(synapser)
synLogin(authToken = "replace-me",
         rememberMe = TRUE,
         silent = TRUE)
submission <- submit_module_answers(module = 0)

If successful, a file with your prediction will be uploaded to Synapse and submitted to the challenge. Youll be able to see the results of your prediction on the miniDREAM scoreboards, with the submission ID that gets printed below.
